<li id="cite_note-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFJames_Oliver_HortonLois_E._Horton2005">James Oliver Horton; Lois E. Horton (2005). <i>Slavery and the Making of America</i>. New York: Oxford University Press. pp.&#160;7. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/019517903X" class="internal">ISBN 0-19-517903-X</a>.  "The slave trade and the products created by slaves' labor, particularly <a href="/wiki/Cotton" title="Cotton">cotton</a>, provided the basis for America's wealth as a nation. Such wealth provided some of the capital for the country's <a href="/wiki/Industrial_Revolution" title="Industrial Revolution">industrial revolution</a> and enabled the United States to project its power into the rest of the world."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Slavery+and+the+Making+of+America&amp;rft.aulast=James+Oliver+Horton&amp;rft.au=James+Oliver+Horton&amp;rft.au=Lois+E.+Horton&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3B7&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=0-19-517903-X&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Slavery_in_the_United_States"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
