<li id="cite_note-49"><b><a href="#cite_ref-49" title="">^</a></b> John Andrew, <i><a href="http://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN073881931X&amp;id=t2Tu-PJxhb0C&amp;pg=PP1&amp;lpg=PP1&amp;ots=yeSrpoXVqP&amp;dq=%22hanging+of+arthur+hodge%22&amp;sig=VroO7PW-JEq1wgBNMGQ9B8V1QNw" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN073881931X&amp;id=t2Tu-PJxhb0C&amp;pg=PP1&amp;lpg=PP1&amp;ots=yeSrpoXVqP&amp;dq=%22hanging+of+arthur+hodge%22&amp;sig=VroO7PW-JEq1wgBNMGQ9B8V1QNw" rel="nofollow">The Hanging of Arthur Hodge</a></i><a href="http://www2.xlibris.com/bookstore/bookdisplay.asp?bookid=970" class="external autonumber" title="http://www2.xlibris.com/bookstore/bookdisplay.asp?bookid=970" rel="nofollow">[1]</a>, <a href="/wiki/Xlibris" title="Xlibris">Xlibris</a>, 2000, <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0738819301" class="internal">ISBN 0-7388-1930-1</a>. The assertion is probably correct; there appear to be no other records of any British slave owners being executed for holding slaves, and, given the excitement which the Hodge trial created, it seems improbable that another execution could have occurred without attracting attention. Slavery as an institution in the British West Indies only continued for another 23 years after Hodge's death.</li>
